{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503575"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:03:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2047"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2047"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.29,0.04,0.44,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76670"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2047"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2020-09-09T08:23:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-04T13:58:01+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2021-06-30T08:13:19+09:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 11:23:33"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2047"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"1034"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37897"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62167"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76670"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a ten-day history of increasing breathlessness and a non-productive cough. She has a medical history of scleroderma, hypertension, and breast cancer. The breast cancer was treated two years previously with neoadjuvant chemotherapy and trastuzumab, followed by surgery, radiotherapy, and 12 months of trastuzumab. She takes amlodipine for her hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 92/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her heart sounds are muffled and her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 8 cm above the sternal angle. There are no additional lung sounds. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radiation-induced cardiomyopathy","Trastuzumab-induced cardiomyopathy","Viral myocarditis","Malignant pericardial effusion","Scleroderma-induced cardiomyopathy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with cardiac tamponade, which is most likely due to a \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignant pericardial effusion\u003C/strong\u003E given her history of breast cancer. The patient exhibits Beck\u0027s triad, which is characteristic of cardiac tamponade: muffled heart sounds, elevated jugular venous pressure, and hypotension. The recent onset of symptoms and the absence of other signs of heart failure make a malignant pericardial effusion the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadiation-induced cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential long-term complication of chest radiotherapy. However, it typically develops years after treatment and would not present acutely with signs of tamponade. It usually manifests as a dilated cardiomyopathy with signs of congestive heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrastuzumab-induced cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a known side effect of this targeted therapy for HER2-positive breast cancer. However, it typically occurs during treatment or shortly after, not two years later. Moreover, it presents as a dilated cardiomyopathy with reduced ejection fraction, not as tamponade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral myocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause acute heart failure, but it would be unlikely to cause a pericardial effusion large enough to result in tamponade. Additionally, patients with myocarditis often have a preceding viral illness and may present with chest pain, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma-induced cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible complication in patients with scleroderma. However, it typically presents as a restrictive cardiomyopathy or with conduction abnormalities, not with acute tamponade. The acute presentation and the history of breast cancer make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMalignant pericardial effusion is a known complication of advanced breast cancer. The fluid accumulates in the pericardial space, eventually leading to tamponade if left untreated. The management of this condition typically involves urgent pericardiocentesis to relieve the pressure on the heart, followed by further investigation and treatment of the underlying malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beck\u0027s triad is indicative of cardiac tamponade and is characterised by muffled heart sounds, elevated jugular venous pressure, and low blood pressure.","Malignant pericardial effusion is a common complication of advanced breast cancer and can lead to cardiac tamponade.","Cardiac tamponade requires urgent intervention, typically pericardiocentesis, to relieve pressure on the heart."],"references":["Stashko E, Meer JM. Cardiac Tamponade. [Updated 2020 Nov 18]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK431090/","Ikeda H, Kikawa Y, Nakamoto Y, Takeo M, Yamamoto M. A patient with recurrent breast cancer showing long-term survival after developing pericardial effusion and cardiac tamponade caused by carcinomatous pericarditis. Breast Care (Basel). 2013 Mar;8(1):71-3. doi: 10.1159/000346831. PMID: 24715847; PMCID: PMC3971803.","Mudra SE, Rayes D, Kumar AK, Li JZ, Njus M, McGowan K, Charalampous C, Kalam KA, Syed A, Majid M, Schleicher M, Agrawal A, Yesilyaprak A, Klein AL. Malignant Pericardial Effusion: A Systematic Review. CJC Open. 2024 May 15;6(8):967-972. doi: 10.1016/j.cjco.2024.05.003. PMID: 39211754; PMCID: PMC11357784."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2047"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T05:03:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-04T13:58:32+09:30","number":5,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-06-04T13:57:59+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-2047-5.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T013333Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=ad4612e68bf7a70919b6ee73f0b462c74e9bde1f6dae5ae7b65091c6ff1c686d"},"relationships"